Named Probability Distributions


Yuji Saikai
ysaikai@unimelb.edu.au
School of Mathematics and Statistics
The University of Melbourne

These notes are based on Chapter 15 & 16 of Jones, O., Maillardet, R., & Robinson, A. (2009). Introduction to scientific programming and simulation using R. CRC Press.


Building upon probability theory, we are going to study specific probability distributions in these notes. They are so common and/or important that each has got a name and dedicated R built-in functions. Although at some point we may need to create special distributions and write associated functions for our models, it is often sufficient to combine the existing ones as building blocks. So, lets master them and get prepared for stochastic modelling.

Discrete distributions

R recognises common distributions by short names and specifies them by parameters.

Distribution R name R Parameters Abbreviation
Bernoulli binom size=1, prob \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\)
Binomial binom size, prob \(\mathrm{binom}(n,p)\)
Geometric geom prob \(\mathrm{geom}(p)\)
Negative binomial nbinom size, prob \(\mathrm{nbinom}(r,p)\)
Poisson pois lambda \(\mathrm{pois}(\lambda)\)

As you see below, \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\) is equivalent to \(\mathrm{binom}(1,p)\).

R built-in functions for common distributions follow a certain pattern. Suppose that a distribution is recognised by name xyz and specified by parameters p1 and p2, then R provides the following four functions to help you work with the distribution.

  • dxyz(x, p1, p2, ...) returns \(P(X=x)\), the value of PMF at \(x\).
  • pxyz(q, p1, p2, ...) returns \(F(q)\), the value of CDF at \(q\).
  • qxyz(p, p1, p2, ...) returns \(\operatorname{argmin}_x F(x)\geq p\), i.e., the quantile function.
  • rxyz(n, p1, p2, ...) returns \(n\) random samples.

In these notes, I avoid using \(p(x)\) for PMF but use \(P(X=x)\) to describe the distribution of \(X\) since we are going to use lots of \(p\) below.

The support of \(X\) means the set \(\{x\in\mathbb{R} : P(X=x)>0\}\) for discrete \(X\) or \(\{x\in\mathbb{R} : f(x)>0\}\) for continuous \(X\) where \(f\) is a PDF of \(X\).

Bernoulli

The support is \(\{0,1\}\), which is often interpreted as failure and success respectively. Naturally, it has a single success parameter \(p\in(0,1)\) that specifies the probability of success, i.e.\(p = P(X=1)\).

Bernoulli distribution serves as a building block and, as you will see below, many complex distributions are modelled as a sequence of independent Bernoulli trials.

\[\begin{align} P(X=x) &= \begin{cases} p & \text{for } x=1\\ 1 - p & \text{for } x=0 \end{cases}\\\\ \mathbb{E}X &= \sum_{x\in\{0,1\}} xP(X=x)\\ &= 0\cdot(1-p)+1\cdot p\\ &= p\\\\ \operatorname{Var} X &= \sum_{x\in\{0,1\}} (x-p)^2P(X=x)\\ &= (0-p)^2\cdot(1-p) + (1-p)^2\cdot p\\ &= p(1-p) \end{align}\]

Binomial

Imagine doing independent \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\) trials \(n\) times. Let \(X\) denote the number of \(1\)s from \(n\) trials. Then, \(X\sim \text{binom}(n,p)\).

Formally, let \(B_1,\dots,B_n \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p)\). Then, \[ X = B_1+\dots+B_n .\] Due to the \(n\) Bernoulli trials, the support is \(\{0,1,\dots,n\}\).

In deriving the PMF, key computation is to count the number of ways to choose \(x\) trials that turn out \(1\) from the total \(n\) trials, commonly denoted by \(\binom{n}{x}\).

\[\begin{align} P(X=x) &= \binom{n}{x}p^x(1-p)^{n-x}\\\\ \mathbb{E}X &= \mathbb{E}(B_1+\dots+B_n)\\ &= \mathbb{E}B_1+\dots+\mathbb{E}B_n\\ &= np\\\\ \operatorname{Var} X &= \operatorname{Var}(B_1+\dots+B_n)\\ &= \operatorname{Var}B_1+\dots+\operatorname{Var}B_n\\ &= np(1-p) \end{align}\]

\(\operatorname{Var} X\) formula is drived by exploiting \(n\) independent Bernoulli trials.

Here are some of PMF plots with varying \(p\).

n <- 8
x <- 0:n
myplot <- function(p) {
  barplot(dbinom(x,n,p),
          names.arg = x,
          ylim=c(0,.5),
          main=paste("binom(",n,", ",p,")", sep=""), 
          xlab="x",
          ylab=expression(P(X==x)))
}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
for (p in c(.2,.5,.7,.9)) {
  myplot(p)
}

Poisson

Imagine doing many independent \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\) trials, in each of which success is very rare. For example, the number of car accidents in Melbourne in a single day, where each of thousands of drivers has a very small chance of accident.

While we may use \(\text{binom}(n,p)\) with large \(n\) and small \(p\), we could be in trouble because computers cannot handle extremely large or small values very well. An alternative modelling option is \(\text{pois}(\lambda)\) with \(\lambda\approx np\). Here is why.

Let \(Y_n \sim \text{binom}(n,p)\) such that \(p=\lambda/n\) for some \(\lambda>0\). Then,

\[\begin{align} P(Y_n=x) &= \binom{n}{x}p^x(1-p)^{n-x}\\ &= \frac{n\cdot(n-1)\dotsm(n-x+1)}{x!}\left(\frac{\lambda}{n}\right)^x\left(1-\frac{\lambda}{n}\right)^{n-x}\\ &= 1\cdot\frac{n-1}{n}\dotsm\frac{n-x+1}{n}\frac{\lambda^x}{x!}\left(1-\frac{\lambda}{n}\right)^{n}\left(1-\frac{\lambda}{n}\right)^{-x}\\ &\to 1\cdot 1\dotsm 1\frac{\lambda^x}{x!}e^{-\lambda}1 \text{ as } n\to\infty\\ &= \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!} \end{align}\]

which is the PMF of \(\mathrm{pois}(\lambda)\). The limit \[ \lim_{n\to\infty} P(Y_n=x) = \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^x}{x!} \] is called the law of rare events.

As indicated by \(n\to\infty\), the support is \(\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}=\{0,1,\dots\}\).

Both mean and variance are equal to \(\lambda\).

An important property of \(\text{pois}(\lambda)\) is the following. Suppose \(X_1,\dots,X_n\) are independent Poisson random variables with the corresponding parameters \(\lambda_1,\dots\lambda_n\). Then, \[ X_1+\dots+X_n = \text{pois}(\lambda_1+\dots+\lambda_n) .\] Here is a proof for \(n=2\), which lets us generalise to \(n>2\) by induction.

\[\begin{align} P(X_1+X_2=n) &= \sum_{m=0}^n P(X_1=m)P(X_2=n-m)\\ &= \sum_{m=0}^n \frac{e^{-\lambda_1} \lambda_1^m}{m!}\cdot\frac{e^{-\lambda_2} \lambda_2^{n-m}}{(n-m)!}\\ &= \frac{e^{-(\lambda_1+\lambda_2)} (\lambda_1+\lambda_2)^n}{n!} \cdot \sum_{m=0}^n\binom{n}{m}\left(\frac{\lambda_1}{\lambda_1+\lambda_2}\right)^m\left(\frac{\lambda_2}{\lambda_1+\lambda_2}\right)^{n-m}\\ &= \frac{e^{-(\lambda_1+\lambda_2)} (\lambda_1+\lambda_2)^n}{n!} \end{align}\]

because the summand is the PMF for \(\text{binom}\left(n,\frac{\lambda_1}{\lambda_1+\lambda_2}\right)\).

Lets compare \(X\sim \text{pois}(\lambda)\) and \(Y\sim \text{binom}(n,p)\) such that \(\lambda = np\). Suppose \(\lambda=1\) for simplicity and \(n=10^4\).

lambda <- 1
n <- 1e4
x <- c(0,2,5)
\(x\) \(P(X=x)\) \(P(Y=x)\)
0 0.3678794 0.367861
2 0.1839397 0.1839489
5 0.0030657 0.003064

Even with a moderate \(n\), Poisson provides reasonable approximation of Binomial.

Here are some of PMF plots with varying \(\lambda\).

n <- 12
x <- 0:n
myplot <- function(l) {
  barplot(dpois(x,l),
          names.arg = x,
          ylim=c(0,.6),
          main=paste("pois(",l,")", sep=""), 
          xlab="x",
          ylab=expression(P(X==x)))
}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
for (l in c(.5,1,2,5)) {
  myplot(l)
}

Geometric

Imagine doing independent \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\) trials indefinitely until we see the first success. Let \(X\) denote the number of \(0\) before getting the first \(1\). Then, \(X\sim \text{geom}(p)\).

N.B. Some authors define \(X\) to be the number of trials, and we also do so in Poisson process below.

Formally, let \(B_1,B_2\dots \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p)\). Then, \[ X = \inf\{n\in\mathbb{Z}_{>0} : B_n=1\}-1 .\]

We cannot really use \(\min\{ \}\) because technically, albeit extremely unlikely, it may never happen.

Given the definition, the support is \(\mathbb{Z}_{\geq0}=\{0,1,\dots\}\).

The derivation of PMF is easier than \(\text{binom}(n,p)\), as it simply continues to multiply the failure probability \(1-p\) until the last success probability \(p\).

\[\begin{align} P(X=x) &= P(B_1=0,B_2=0,\dots,B_x=0,B_{x+1}=1))\\ &= P(B_1=0) \dotsm P(B_x=0)P(B_{x+1}=1)\\ &= (1-p)^xp\\\\ \mathbb{E}X &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty xP(X=x)\\ &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty x(1-p)^xp\\ &= p(1-p)\sum_{x=0}^\infty x(1-p)^{x-1}\\ &= p(1-p)\left(-\sum_{x=0}^\infty \frac{d}{dp}(1-p)^{x}\right)\\ &= p(1-p)\frac{d}{dp}\left(-\sum_{x=0}^\infty (1-p)^{x}\right)\\ &= p(1-p)\frac{d}{dp}\left(-\frac{1}{p}\right)\\ &= \frac{1-p}{p} \end{align}\]

For the variance, lets first compute \(\mathbb{E}[X(X-1)]\). \[\begin{align} \mathbb{E}[X(X-1)] &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty x(x-1)(1-p)^xp\\ &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty p(1-p)^2x(x-1)(1-p)^{x-2}\\ &= p(1-p)^2 \sum_{x=0}^\infty \frac{d^2}{dp^2}(1-p)^{x}\\ &= p(1-p)^2 \frac{d^2}{dp^2}\sum_{x=0}^\infty (1-p)^{x}\\ &= p(1-p)^2 \frac{d^2}{dp^2}\frac{1}{p}\\ &= \frac{2(1-p)^2}{p^2}\\ \end{align}\]

Now, \[\begin{align} \operatorname{Var} X &= \mathbb{E}X^2 - (\mathbb{E}X)^2\\ &= \mathbb{E}[X(X-1)] + \mathbb{E}X - (\mathbb{E}X)^2\\ &= \frac{2(1-p)^2}{p^2} + \frac{1-p}{p} - \frac{(1-p)^2}{p^2}\\ &= \frac{1-p}{p^2} \end{align}\]

We may interchange the order of summation and differentiation in geometric series.

Here are some of PMF plots with varying \(p\).

n <- 8
x <- 0:n
myplot <- function(p) {
  barplot(dgeom(x,p),
          names.arg = x,
          ylim=c(0,.8),
          main=paste("geom(",p,")", sep=""), 
          xlab="x",
          ylab=expression(P(X==x)))
}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
for (p in c(.2,.4,.6,.8)) {
  myplot(p)
}

Negative binomial

Despite the possibly confusing name, this is simply a generalised version of geometric distribution: instead of the first success, we wait until \(r\) successes.

Imagine doing independent \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\) trials indefinitely until we see \(r\) successes. Let \(X\) denote the number of \(0\) before getting \(r\) number of \(1\)s. Then, \(X\sim \text{nbinom}(r,p)\).

Conveniently, we may see \(X\sim \text{nbinom}(r,p)\) as the sum of \(r\) independent \(\text{geom}(p)\) random variables. Thus, the mean and variance are particularly easy to compute:

\[\begin{align} \mathbb{E}X &= r\frac{1-p}{p}\\ \operatorname{Var} X &= r\frac{1-p}{p^2} \end{align}\]

To derive the PMF, notice first the following. If the \(r\)-th success is on trial \(y\), then the previous \(r-1\) successes can occur anywhere in the previous \(y1\) trials. Thus, there are \(\binom{y-1}{r-1}\) ways we can get the \(r\)-th success on the \(y\)-th trial. Each of these ways has probability \((1-p)^{y-r}p^r\), so putting \(x=y-r\), we get: \[P(X=x) = \binom{r+x-1}{r-1}(1-p)^{x}p^r .\]

Here are some of PMF plots with varying \(p\).

n <- 8
x <- 0:n
myplot <- function(p) {
  barplot(dnbinom(x,4,p),
          names.arg = x,
          ylim=c(0,.5),
          main=paste("nbinom(",4,", ",p,")", sep=""), 
          xlab="x",
          ylab=expression(P(X==x)))
}
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
for (p in c(.2,.4,.6,.8)) {
  myplot(p)
}

Continuous distributions

R recognises common distributions by short names and specifies them by parameters.

Distribution R name R Parameters Abbreviation
Uniform unif min, max \(\mathrm{U}(a,b)\)
Exponential exp rate \(\exp(\lambda)\)
Weibull weibull shape, scale \(\mathrm{weibull}(m,\lambda)\)
Gamma gamma shape, rate \(\text{gamma}(m,\lambda)\)
Normal norm mean, sd \(\mathrm{N}(\mu,\sigma^2)\)

R built-in functions for common distributions follow a certain pattern. Suppose that a distribution is recognised by name xyz and specified by parameters p1 and p2, then R provides the following four functions to help you work with the distribution.

  • dxyz(x, p1, p2, ...) returns \(f(x)\), the value of PDF at \(x\).
  • pxyz(q, p1, p2, ...) returns \(F(q)\), the value of CDF at \(q\).
  • qxyz(p, p1, p2, ...) returns \(\operatorname{argmin}_x F(x)\geq p\), i.e., the quantile function.
  • rxyz(n, p1, p2, ...) returns \(n\) random samples.

Uniform

\(X\sim \mathrm{U}(a,b)\) if the support of \(X\) is an interval \([a,b]\) and the density is independent of location \(x\).

Deriving the PDF of \(X\) highlights key ideas common in many continuous distributions. The ideas to recall are:

  • \(f(x)\) is equal to \(0\) for \(x\) outside the support,
  • \(f(x)\) integrates to \(1\) over the real line.

Given \(X\sim \mathrm{U}(a,b)\), let \(c=f(x)\) for \(x\in[a,b]\). Then, \[ f(x) = \begin{cases} c & \text{if } x\in[a,b]\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \] It follows:

\[\begin{alignat}{2} & & \int_{-\infty}^\infty f(x)dx &= 1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad & \int_a^b cdx &= 1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad & c(b-a) &= 1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad & c &= \frac{1}{b-a} \end{alignat}\]

Just like the role \(\mathrm{Bernoulli}(p)\) plays in constructing discrete distributions, as you will see in Sampling Methods, \(\mathrm{U}(0,1)\) is a fundamental device for sampling from pretty much any distribution in silico.

Exponential

\(X\sim \mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\) has the following PDF: \[ f(x) = \begin{cases} \lambda e^{-\lambda x} & \text{if } x\geq0\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \] with rate parameter \(\lambda>0\).

The CDF is equal to \(0\) for \(x<0\) and, for \(x\geq0\), \[\begin{align} F(x) &= \int_{-\infty}^x f(t)dt\\ &= \int_0^x \lambda e^{-\lambda t} dt\\ &= 1-e^{-\lambda x} \end{align}\]

In practice, \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\) is often used to model waiting time. For given waiting time \(x\), large \(\lambda\) implies fast arrival rate and high probability of arrival, indicated by \(F(x)\) as an increasing function of \(\lambda\).

In contrast, given any arrival rate \(\lambda\), if we wait forever (\(x\to\infty\)), it almost surely arrives as indicated by \(F(x)\to 1\).

Memoryless property

Unique to \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\) is the so-called momoryless property, which can be expressed as follows. \[ P(X>t+s | X>t) = P(X>s) \;\text{ for } s,t>0 .\]

A proof simple. \[\begin{align} P(X>t+s | X>t) &= \frac{P(X>t+s, X>t)}{P(X>t)}\\ &= \frac{P(X>t+s)}{P(X>t)}\\ &= \frac{e^{-\lambda(t+s)}}{e^{-\lambda(t)}}\\ &= e^{-\lambda s}\\ &= P(X>s) \end{align}\]

To illustrate, lets use \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\) to model the waiting time for an elevator. Suppose \(\lambda = 0.5\). Then, the probability that an elevator arrives within 4 minutes, is \(F(4) = 0.86\).

Today is your bad day, and it has not come after waiting for 4 minutes. Now, you wonder Since I already waited for so long and I know \(F(5) = 0.92\) (nerd!), it will very likely come within a minute.

The memoryless property says Not really. It will come only with \(F(1) = 0.39\) chance. In other words, if your mental model relies on \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\), the fact that you have already waited for so long is totally irrelevant.

Weibull

When modelling arrival of bad things (e.g., mechanical failure or disaster), we often phrase it as survival, simply meaning the negation of arrival. In probabilistic terms, if \(F(x)\) is the probability that a failure happens by the time \(x\), \(1-F(x)\) is the probability of survival until the time \(x\).

While \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\) can be used, \(\mathrm{weibull}(m,\lambda)\) provides a more general framework, which is often more suitable for survival analysis. The PDF \(f(x)\) and CDF \(F(x)\) are given below.

\[\begin{align} f(x) &= \begin{cases} m\lambda x^{m-1}e^{-\lambda x^m} & \text{if } x\geq0\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}\\\\ F(x) &= \begin{cases} 1 - e^{-\lambda x^m} & \text{if } x\geq0\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}\\\\ \end{align}\]

\(\mathrm{weibull}(m,\lambda)\) generalises the constant rate \(\lambda\) used in \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\) to a function \(\lambda(x) = m\lambda x^{m-1}\), which covers the constant case at \(m=1\). This time-varying rate \(\lambda(x)\) is commonly referred to as a hazard function.

Hazard function

For \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\), the rate parameter \(\lambda\) is assumed to be constant. What if our real-world problems suggest that the arrival/survival rate is not constant but depends on \(x\)?

We begin with the CDF of \(\mathrm{exp}(\lambda)\): \[ F(x) = 1-e^{-\lambda x} .\] Recall that \(\lambda\) captures a rate (e.g., a derivative or a change for an infinitesimal time), and \(F(x)\) is the probability of occurrence by the time \(x\), which goes to \(1\) as \(x\to\infty\). This observation suggests that \(\lambda x\) is the result of integration, \(\lambda x = \int_0^x \lambda dt\).

Now, lets explicitly write \(\lambda(x)\) as a function of \(x\). As long as we make sure \(\int_0^x \lambda(t) dt\) is an increasing function of \(x\), we have a legitimate \(F(x)\) such that \[ \lim_{x\to\infty}F(x) = \lim_{x\to\infty}\left[1-\exp\left(-\int_0^x \lambda(t)dt\right)\right] = 1 .\]

With this CDF, the PDF can be derived using the chain rule and the fundamental theorem of calculus.

\[\begin{align} f(x) &= F'(x)\\ &= \frac{d}{dx}\left[1-\exp\left(-\int_0^x \lambda(t)dt\right)\right]\\ &= \lambda(x)\exp\left(-\int_0^x \lambda(t)dt\right), \end{align}\]

which is the PDF of \(\mathrm{weibull}(m,\lambda)\) if \(\lambda(x) = m\lambda x^{m-1}\).

R parameterisation

This is unfortunately confusing but important to note. The R parameterisation of the Weibull distribution differs from that presented here. shape parameter in R simply corresponds to \(m\). But, scale in R corresponds to \(\lambda^{-1/m}\).

For example, to simulate \(\mathrm{weibull}(m,\lambda)\) with \(m=0.5\) and \(\lambda=2\), give

  • shape=0.5
  • scale=2^(-1/0.5)

to each of R built-in functions for \(\mathrm{weibull}(m,\lambda)\).

Gamma

As seen in Exponential, \(\text{exp}(\lambda)\) is commonly used to model waiting time. Dividing the continuous time line into small intervals of equal length, we may model waiting-time problems using \(\text{geom}(p)\), which is a sequence of IID \(\text{Bernoulli}(p)\). That is, at each interval, \(\text{Bernoulli}(p)\) represents an occurrence of arrival.

Remember that if we add \(r\) number of IID \(\text{geom}(p)\), we get \(\text{nbinom}(r,p)\). Therefore, it is natural to wonder what if we add \(m\) number of IID \(\text{exp}(\lambda)\). The answer is \(\text{gamma}(m,\lambda)\).

Let \(X = Y_1+\dots+Y_m\) such that \(Y_i\sim\text{exp}(\lambda)\) for all \(i\in\{1,\dots,m\}\). Then, \(X\) follows \(\text{gamma}(m,\lambda)\).

Normal

Because of its incredible analytical properties, normal distribution is arguably the most important probability distribution. To highlight just two of those properties, we use random vector which are jointly distributed as normal.

Scalar \(X\sim \mathrm{N}(\mu,\sigma^2)\) is a special case. By now, you should be capable of using R built-in functions for norm.

Let \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) be the mean vector of length \(n\) and \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) be the \(n\times n\) covariance matrix (hence, positive-semidefinite).

Property 1

Let \(\mathbf{Z}\) be the standardised \(\mathbf{X}\), namely, \(\mathbf{Z}\sim \mathrm{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}_m)\), where \(\mathbf{I}_m\) is the \(m\times m\) identity matrix. Then, there exist a \(n\times m\) matrix \(\mathbf{A}\) such that \(\mathbf{A}\mathbf{A}'=\mathbf{\Sigma}\) and \[\mathbf{X} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{Z}+\boldsymbol{\mu} .\]

An implication is that since \(\mathbf{Z}\) is merely \(m\) independent \(\mathrm{N}(0,1)\) stacked as a vector, it is easy to simulate \(\mathbf{Z}\) and thereby simulating \(\mathbf{X}\).

To generate a sample \(\mathbf{x}\) of \(\mathbf{X}\) with your desirable \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) and \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\),

  1. Decompose \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) into \(\mathbf{A}\) and \(\mathbf{A}'\) (typically via Cholesky decomposition),
  2. Simulate \(\mathrm{N}(0,1)\) \(n\) times and stack them as \(\mathbf{z}\),
  3. Compute \(\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{z}+\boldsymbol{\mu}\).

Yes, of course, theres a package for that! But, it is quite fulfilling to know a sampling algorithm for such an important random vector. Once you get it and test your own, you may use function mvrnorm from MASS package.

Property 2

The second property is, in words, a linear transformation of \(\mathbf{x}\) is also normal.

Let \(\mathbf{C}\) be a \(m\times n\) matrix. Then, \[\mathbf{C}\mathbf{X} \sim \mathbf{N}(\mathbf{C}\boldsymbol{\mu}, \mathbf{C}\mathbf{\Sigma}\mathbf{C}') .\]

For example, if \(\mathbf{C} = (c_1\;c_2\;\dots\;c_n)\) is a \(1\times n\) matrix, then we have the sum \(\mathbf{C}\mathbf{X} = c_1X_1+c_2X_2+\dots+c_nX_n\).

Furthermore, if \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) is a diagonal or \(\mathbf{X}\) is formed by stacking \(n\) independent \(\mathrm{N}(\mu_i,\sigma_i^2)\), then we have a common statement the sum of independent normals is normal.

Joint PDF

If \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) is a \(n\times n\) positive-definite covariance matrix, then normal random vector \(\mathbf{X} \sim \mathrm{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu},\mathbf{\Sigma})\) has a joint PDF: \[f(\mathbf{x}) = (2\pi)^{-\frac{n}{2}}|\mathbf{\Sigma}|^{-\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{x}-\boldsymbol{\mu})'\mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1}(\mathbf{x}-\boldsymbol{\mu})\right)\] where \(|\mathbf{\Sigma}|\) is the determinant of \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\).
